{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340582986/1920070901/0189.xml":{"full_text":"Pools Dominated the Trad\ning In Selected Stocks as\nAgainst the Representa\ntive Shares\nBy Associated Press\n1 New York, July 8.\u2014The stock mar\nI het was fairly active and strong again\ntoday, although falling somewhat be\ni low yesterday\u2019s extensive operations,\nj both in volume and variety of dealings.\nI Movements of leaders were influenced\nto a greater degree by intermittent\nprofit taking.\nPools dominated the trading, this be\ning clearly demonstrated by the further\nprominence of selected stocks as\nagainst the irregular trend of repre\nsentative shares, but there were indi\ncations of renewed absorption of rails,\nespecially the junior speculative issues.\nPublic interest locally was light, but\ncommission houses reported further\nsigns of a July reinvestment demand\nfrom out-of-town, notably in high\ngrade industrials and several of the\nlatest capital underwritings.\nThe success of the Swiss loan stimu\nlated interest in the forthcoming of\nfering by a banking syndicate of $60,\n000,000 of Armour Co. ten-year, 7 per\ncent convertible notes, formal an\nnouncement of which was made after\nthe close of the market.\nThere was again a visible dearth of\ntime funds, but call money continued\nto ease on an enlarged supply. The\nopening qoutation of 7 per cent, which\nheld throughout the session, was the\nlowest in many weeks.\nChanges in the foreign remittance\nmarket were nominal, the British rate\neasing, with similar tendencies in the\nmore important continental rates. Deal\ners reported a moderate inquiry for ru\nhies (currency bills) presumably in\nconsequence of the lifting of the trade\nembargo on soviet Russia. The Bank\nof England statement showed a sub\nstantial recovery of liabilty reserves.\nConvertible railway issues and Cu\nban fives, the latter at an advance of 2\npoints, featured the firm bond market,\nalthough Liberty issues were again ir\nregular. Total sales, par value, aggre\ngated $11,775,000. Old IT. S. 4s rose\non call, other unchanged.\nNew York Stock*\nBy Associated Presa\nSales. High.\nAmer. R. S. 1100 96 93%\nAmer. Can 3500 43% 43\nAmer. C.- ft F.. 4900 142% 141\nAmer. H. ft L.,\npfd 200 93 93\nAmer. Tnt. C... 5800 90% 89%\nAmer. Loco 21600 104% 102%\nAmer. Linseed 1400 81 80\nAmer. S. ft R... 3300 62% 62\nAmer. Sugar. 1600 127% 125%\nAmer. S. Tob... 400 93 91%\nAmer. T. T. 500 93% 93%\nAmer. Woolen 6700 101 98\nAnacondo Cop. 3400 58% 57%\nAtchison 1900 80% 80%\nA11. C. L. 200 85% 85\nAtl. G. ft W. I. 2300 169% 166\nBald. Loco.... 31700 126% 125%\nPalto. ft Ohio.. 2900 32% 31%\nBeth. Steel *\u2018B' 4800 92% 91%\n^Canadian Pac.. 1600 117% 116%\n^Central Leath-.. 500 69% 69%\nChandler Mo.. 2500 105 104\nChesa. ft Ohio 2400 54 53%\nChi., M. ft St. P. 6300 34% 33%\nChi.. R. T. ft P. 17400 39% 37%\nChino Copper.. 1900 31% 31%\nCoca-Cola 700 35% 35%\nCol. F. ft T. 400 35 35\nCorn Prod. 7100 97% 96%\nCrucible Steel 15600 162% 159%\nCuba C. S. 4500 54% 54\nErie 800 12% 12\nGen. Electric.. 300 142% 142\nGen. Motors.. 65700 28 27%\ntit. Nor. pfd.. 2200 70% 70\nGt. Nor. O. C... 200 36% 36%\nGulf S. S. 1800 63% 63\nIllinois Central 100 82% 82%\n1 nspir. Cop_ 7800 54% 52%\nInter. Mer.\nMarine, pfd.. 900 94% 94%\nInter. Nickel 3900 18% 17%\nInter. Paper.\n21000 82% 80\nKenne. Copper 1800 27% 26%\nTvouis. ft Nash.. 100 102% 102%\nMex. Petrol.. 10600 198 195%\nMiami Copper.. 200 21% 21%\nMiddle S. Oil.. 4300 32%\nMidvale Steel.. 4500 43\nMo. pacific_ 3900 26\nN. Central. 1600 69%\nX. Y_ N. H. ft\nHartford 8500 31\nNorfolk ft West. 200 90% 90%\nNorthern Pac.. 1 300 72% 71%\njfliiio Cities G... 1200\n4%\n31%\n42%\n25\n68%\n39%\n4%\nif JlIJO V llies lx.. JtfVU t 74\np Pan-Amer. P... 0100 108 Vi 107 V4\n39 V*\nS7V*\n96%\n1214\n77%\n7U\n12H\n76%\n32%\n74\n93%\n26 U\n58\n41%\n71\nf Pennsylvania 2600 39%\nPitts.. W. Va. 1800 30% 30\nRay Con. Cop... 1600 16% 16%\nReading. 15600 88%\nRep. T. S. 14200 98%\nRoval Dutch,\nN. Y. 4800 115% 114%\nSeaboard A. L. 100\ndo pfd 200\n.Shell T. T... 1800\nSine. O. R_ 6200 33\nSloss-Sheff.\nSteel Iron. 1800 75\n\u2022Southern Pac. 10500 94%\nSouthern Ry.. 23000 27%\ndo pfd 700 58%\nStandard Oil of\nN. J.. pfd 3700 104% 104%\nFfude. Corp.. 165O0 78 76\nTenn. Copper.. 1500 10% 10\nTexas Co. 7700 48 47%\nTexas Pac. 10500 43\nTob. Products. 1700 71\nTrans. Oil. 2200 167% 166%\nUnion Pacific. 7*00 115 114%\nUnited Fruit i00n 205% 203%\nU. S Food Prod. 7200 72 70%\nV. S. Tnd. Abo. 1900 97% 96\nr. S. Retail S. 2900 81% 80%\nT\\ S. Rubber.. 6900 101 100%\nr. S. Steel_ 20800 05% 94%\ndo pfd 900 109 108\nUtah Copper... 1600 70 69%\na.-Caro. ('hem. 900 75% 74%\n'estern Union\nfWestlngr\u2019h. Elec. 700 50%\nWillys-Over-. 21100 20%\nTotal sales, 797,300.\nNew York Bonds\nTT. R. 2s, registered, bid\nU. R. 2s. coupon, bid.\nTT. R. 4s. registered, bid\nU. S. 4s, coupon, bid\nPanama 3s. registered, hid\nPanama 3s, coupon, bid.\nr,n\n19%\nClose.\n96\n43%\n141\n93\n89%\n103 y,\n81\n62%\n127%\n92 74\n93%\n98\n57%\n80%\n85%\n167%\n126\n32\n92\n117\n69%\n104%\n54\n34%\n37%\n31%\n35%\n35%\n96%\n160%\n54%\n12%\n142%\n27%\n70\n36%\n63\n82%\n53%\n94%\n18%\n82%\n27\n102%\n196%\n21%\n32%\n42 74\n25%\n69%\n30 74\n90%\n72\n4%\n107%\n39%\n30\n16%\n87%\n97%\n11474\n7%\n12%\n76%\n32%\n75%\n93%\n27%\n58%\n104%\n74%\n10%\n47%\n42%\n71\n166%\n114%\n205\n71%\n96\n80%\n100%\n95\n108\n69%\n75%\nS3\n50\n20\n100%\n100%\n104%\n105%\n77\n77\n\nWe are accepting\nsubscriptions for\nnow offering of\nThe Goodyear\nTire Rubber\nCompany\nPreferred and Common\nStocks\nFull particulars\non request\nMarx and Co.\nBANKERS\n\n\nAmerican Smelting Refining 5s\nAmerican Tel. Tel. cv 6s\nAnglo-French 5s\nAtchison gen. 4s\nAtlantic Coast Line 1st 4s\nBaltimore Ohio cv. 4%s\nBethlehem Steel ref. 5s\nCentral of Georgia con. os\nCentral leather 5s, tyid\nChesapeake Ohio cv. 5s\nChicago, B. Quincy joint os..\nChicago. Mil. St. T. cv. 4%s\nChicago. R. I. Pac. ref. 4s..\nCity of Paris 6s\nColorado Southern ref. 4%\u00bb..\nDenver Rio Grande con. 4s\nDominion of Canada 5s (1931)..\nErie gen. 4s. bid\nIllinois Ceneral ref. 4s\nInter. Merchant Marine 6s. bid..\nKansas City Southern ref. 5s\nLiggett Myers 5s. bid.\nLouift. Nash. un. 4s\nMo., Kan. Texas 1st 4s\nMissouri Pac. gen. 4s\nNew York Central deb. 6s\nNorfolk Western cv. 6s\nNorthern Pacific 4s\nPennsylvania gen. 5s.\nReeling gen. 4s\nRepublic Iron S. 5s (1940), bid\nSt. Louis San Fran adj. 6s\nSeaboard Air Line adj. 5s\nSouthern Bell Telephone 5s.\nSouthern Pacific cv. 5s\nSouthern Railway 5s\nSouthern Railway gen. 4s\nUnion Pacific 1st. bid\nUnited Kingdom of G. B.\nI. 5%s (1937)\nU. S. Steel 5s\nVirginia-Caro. Chemical 5s. bid\nWabash 1st\nWilson Co. cv. 6s\n77%\n93%\n99\n72\n78%\n58 V.\n78$\n91 Vi\n75 Vi\n94\n62\n617*\n94\n67\n61\n$6%\n39\n70\n84\n661 j\n77\n77 Vi\n5 3 Vi\n51 Vi\n86%\n96\nS3\n75 Vi\n85\n61*4\n33 V,\n85\n95*4\n7S%\n76\nn%\n91 Vi\n91\n82\n85\nLiberty Bonds\nBy Associated Press\nNew York. July 8.\u2014Final prices to\nday were:\n3%s 91.20\nFirst 4s 86.40\nSecond 4s 86.66\nFirst 4 ViS 86.40\nSecond 4Vis 85.70\nThird 4V4 89.70\nFourth 4 V4a 85.94\nVictory 3%s 95.86\nVictory 4%s 95.88\nMoney Market\nBy Associated Press\nNew York, July 8.\u2014Mercantile paper.\n7%S per cent; exchange irregular. Sterl\ning 60-day bills. $3.89%; commercial 60\nday bills on banks. $3.89%; commercial\n60-day bills, $3.89: demand. $3.91: cables,\n$3.94%. Francs: Demand. 8.32; cables, 8.34.\nBelgian francs: Demand. 8.9S: cables. 9.\nGuilders: Demand. 35.25; cables. 35.27.\nLire: Demand, 6; cables, 6.02. Marks:\nDemand, 2.63; cables, 2M. New York\nexchange on Montreal, 12 3-16. Govern\nment bonds irregular. Railroad bonds\nsteady. Time loans strong; 60 days, 90\ndays and six months, 8% per cent. Bar\nsilver, domestic, 99%c; foreign, 94%c.\nMexican dollars, 77c.\ncank or England\nBy Associated Press\nLondon, July 8.\u2014The weekly statement\nof the Bank of England showed the fol\nlowing changes:\nTotal reserve increased \u00a3170,009.\nCirculation increased \u00a32,686,000.\nBullion increased \u00a32,855,661.\nOther securities decreased \u00a310,294,000.\nPublic deposits increased $2,138,000.\nOther deposits decreased \u00a358.932,000.\nNotes, reserve, increased \u00a362,000.\nGovernment securities decreased \u00a327,*\n654.000.\nThe proportion of the bank\u2019s reserve to\nliability is 12.18 per cent; last ween it\nwas 8.49.\nRate of discount 7 por cent.\nBank of France\nBy Associated Press\nParis, July 8.\u2014The weekly state\nment of the Bank of France shows\nthe folllowing changes: Gold in\ncreased 356.000 francs; silver increased\n5.538.000 francs; notes in circulation in\ncreased 249,413,000 francs; treasury de\nposits increased 7,472,000 francs; gen\neral deposits decreased 298,150,000\nfrancs; bills discounted decreased 201,\n170.000 francs; advances increased 82.\n977.000 francs. New advances to the\nstate amounted to 100,000,000 francs.\nLondon Money\nBy Associated Prsss\nLondon, July 8.\u2014Bar silver, o4d per\nounce; money. 4*4 per cent; discount\nrates, short bills, 6^4 per cent; three\nmonths bills, 6% per cent.\nChicago Live Stock\nBy Associated Press\nChicago, July 8.\u2014Cattle: Receipts, 9.000.\nBeef steers, better grades, fat cows and\nheifers firm to 25c higher.\nTop steers 17.00\nAverage 1,450 pounds, top year\nlings 16.75\nBulk beef steers, all weights.. 13.00@10.65\nCanners, cutters and bulls steady.\nVeal calves, bulk .$12.50@13.75\nHogs: Receipts, 26,000; active, 25c to 35c\nhigher than yesterday\u2019s average; poorer\nadvanced most.\nTop .J IB.ii\nBulk light and butchers.15.80@1B.13\nBulk 250 pounds and over. 13.6a@15.70\nPigs steady to strong:\nBulk desirable kinds. 13.00@13.ad\nEast St. Louis Lire Stock\nBy Au.al.tey Pr*u\nEast St. Louis, July 8.\u2014Cattle: Receipts,\n8.000. Native steers steady; quarantine\nsteers shade lower.\nTop steers .8 14.75\nBulk 11.00@14.00\nCanner cows steady at. 3.75@ 4.50\nHogs: Receipts, 2,000; 10c to 20c lower.\nTop .t 13.65\nBulk light and medium. 15.90@lS.3o\nBulk heavies 15.50@IUW\nSheep: Receipts, 2,000; lambs 25c higher;\nsheep steady.\nTop Iambs .f 14. Id\nBulk 13.50@lt.0ii\nTop ewes S.00\nBulk 5.50@ O.'JO\nCoffee Market\nBy Amelaled Pnn\nNew York, July 8.\u2014The steadier tone re\nported in the market for coffee futures\nyesterday was followed by more active\ncovering and a sharp advance today. The\nbuying was stimulated by reports of ad\nvances In futures at Santos, and thera\nwas also talk of a better jobbing demand,\nwhich \"probably contributed to the\nstrength of the local market.\nFirst prices were somewhat irregular,\nwith July 3 points lower, but later months\nshowed an advance of 10 to 14 points and\nJuly soon firmed up with the rest of the\nlist, which became more active an 1\nfirmer during the afternoon, when spe\ncial cables came in reporting further re\ncoveries in Santos. September sold up to\n12.51c and December to 12.8*c. or 83 1o\n71 points net higher and about ill to !'-\u20194\npoints above the low level of last week.\nClosing prices were at about the best\nof the day, with the general list showing\na net advance of 57 to 8# points. Closing\nbids:\nJuly 13.38c: September, 12.18c; October,\n12.51c: December, 12.58c: January, 12.82c;\nMarch, 12.88c: May, 12.73c.\nSpot coffee was reported in better de\nmand. with the market firmer at 1l,',c\nfor Rio 7a and lJ^iSTlc for Santos 4s. Verv\nfew fresh offers were reported in the\ncost and freight market. Received in\ncluded Santos 4s at 17.50c and Rio 7s at\n12 75c, American credits.\nThe early cables reported no change In\nthe Rio market, with Santos futures 5li\nrels lower to 175 higher. 1-atep two spe\ncial cables were received from Santos,\nthe first of whieh reported an advance\nof 100 to 325 reie and the second Of 73 to\n225 reisa. Brazilian port receipts. 30,W\u00bb:\nJundiahy reoeipts. 14,000. The weather\nwas fine in Sao Paulo with minimum\ntemperatures 44 to 50 degrees.\nSugar Market\n\u25a0y AUeeleM grew\nNew Tork, July 8.\u2014The sugar mar\nket wag quieter today, but the under\ntone wag firmer and prices were high\ner on sales of 1.200 bags of San Do\nmingo and afloat at 17.50c. eif.. to op\nerators, which is about >\u00abic above the\nlast previous sale of this kind of sugar\nThere were no sales of Cabas or Porto\nRicos and while there were no indica\ntions that buyers would pay above the\nlagt sale price, 17lie. holders were ask\ning equivalent to the full doty price, or\n17%c. cost and freight, equal to 18.81r\nDaily Financial Gossip\nBy HOLLAND\nserious danger of business crisis did ex\nist in the early spring of this year is\nnow admitted by the men of finance\nwho were familiar with conditions. They\nknew it at the time, but thought that\nprudence required silence. Now in these\nfirst days of the new fiscal year perhaps\nthe most gratifying report to be made is\none which tells of the passing of the crisis\nand the slow but steady relief from the\nembarrassments which business men met\nwith in the winter and early spring.\nThe crisis was a business embarrass\nment. There was no real danger of\nmoney panic. But business men report\ned in the spring that they were unable\nto forecast the future for more than a\nfew weeks. They did not know whether\nthey would be able to secure needed ac\ncommodations from the banks They\nfeared lest their loans would be called.\nThe farmers felt the pressure and were\nobliged to cancel orders for tractors and\nother farm implements. Many of the\nsales agents were compelled to return the\ntractors which had been placed with\nthem for sale to the manufacturers be\ncause the farmers could not takfe these\nfarming implements.\nWe now- know that in the late fall or\nlast year the bankers of the United\nStates, at least the leading bankers, w'ere\ndivided into two groups. No longer does\na division of this kind exist. One group\nwhich was perhaps the largest and most\ninfluential began in November of last\nyear to insist that rapid deflation should\ntake place. They asserted that continued\ninflation of the currency would not only\nmaintain but increase high prices. The\nmeasures they advocated were to a great\nextent adopted. Loans were called. There\nwas heavy marketing of Liberty Bonds,\nwith increasing depreciation in the mar\nket quotations for them. Deflation was\nbeginning to hurt. The support of cur\nrency for the business of the country\nwas far from sufficient. At the time\nwhen business was calling for money the\nfederal reserve banks were carrying ap\nproximately $1,500,000,000 of government\npaper. If this money had been available\nfor business embarrassment would not\nhave occurred.\nINSISTING ON DEFLATION\nThroughout the winter and the early\nspring the pressure for deflation was\nmaintained, although it was apparent that\nthere was not enough currency avail\nable for the business life of the United\nStates because the government through\nits placing in the federal reserve banks\nof such enormous amounts of government\npaper had absorbed the currency\nOn the other hand a group of bankers\nfor centrifugal. The market for re\nfined was unchanged at 22c to 24c *#o.\u2019\nfine granulated. Two of the refiners\nare still out of the market, but the\ndemand is least active.\nFutures were firmer and after show\ning advances of 8 to 15 points on ac\ntive positions, due to covering and buy\ning by commission houses, there wa\na slight set-back near the close un\nder liquidation, with closing quota\ntions unchanged to 9 points higher foe\nleading months.\nMetal Market\nBy Associated Press\nNew' York, July 8.\u2014Copper steady;\nelectrolytic, spot and third quarter, 19,*\nIron steady; prices unchanged. Tin\nsteady; spot, July and August, 48.75.\nAntimony, 7.75. Metal Exchange quoted\nlead firm; spot and July offered at 8.30.\nZinc quiet; East St. Louis delivery spot,\n7.40 bid. 7.70 asked. At T/ondon: Spot\ncopper. \u00a3S9 12s 6d; futures, \u00a391 17s 6d;\nelectrolytic, spot, \u00a3105; futures, \u00a3110. Tin,\nspot, \u00a3249 5s; futures. \u00a3256 15s. Lead,\nspot. \u00a333 5s; futures. \u00a334 15s. Zinc, spot,\n\u00a341 15s; futures, \u00a343 5s.\nNaval Stores\nBy Associated Press\nJacksonville, July 8.\u2014Turpentine firm,\n$1.35*6; sales, 564; receipts, 775; shipments,\n784; stock, 6,744.\nRosin firm; sales, 2,491; receipts, 2,075;\nshipments, 2,250; stock, 53,625.\nQuote B, $10.25; D. E. F, G, H, T, K, M.\n$13(gl3.10; N, WG and WW, $13.10.\nSavannah, July 8.\u2014Turpentine, firm,\n$1.36; sales, 181; receipts, 1,130; ship\nments, 538; stock. 6,858. Rosin, firm;\nsales, 1.302; receipts, 2,574; shipments,\n1.464; stock. 26,660. Quote: B. $10.25;\nD. F. G, H, I, K. M, $13. N, WG, WW,\n$13.10.\nCotton Seed Oil\nBy Associated Press\nNew York, July 8.\u2014Early weakened\nin the cotton seed oil market, which\nfollowed declines on the grain and cot\nton was replaced later by heavy cov\nering on which prices rallied sharp\nly. helped by the upturn in lard. Final\nslight reactions left the market steady\nat a net decline of 10 to 30 points\nSales, 12,100 barrels. Prime crude,\nnominal; prime summer yellow spot,\nnominal: July, $13.25: September\n$14.15; December. $14. all bid. Prime\nwinter yellow and summer white,\nnominal.\nIron and Steel Review\nCleveland, O., July 8.\u2014(SpeciaU)\u2014The\nIron Trade Review today say.*?: A losing\nbattle, to every sign, is being waged\nby iron and steel producers in tbeir con\ntinuing struggle to maintain operations\nagainst a grossly defiant transportation\nservice centering upon the restricted use\nof open top cars except for coal ship\nments, which is to be in force two weeks\nmore, and the situation has l*een grow\ning steadily worse.\nThe resistance nf the industry to the\nslow strangulation la surprising, as the\ntonnage of finished and semi-finished ma\nterial, backed up at the plants of the\nproducers and still amounting, has passed\nthe point of reliable estimation, so large\nhas it become, frozen credits in thus\nform present a pressing problem even for\nthe strongest interests. Many plants are\nbeing kept going mainly by the use of\nmotor trucks. More than two-thirds of\nthe daily output of some large works\nin the Pittsburg district Is being kept\nmoving in this fashion, supplemented by\nbarges.\nInvestigation being conducted by the\ndepartment of justice into the fairness ot\npresent prices of coal has attracted at\ntention especially as to Its bearing upon\nthe coke market. Furnace in this district\nare taking stronger position against pay\ning the prevailing prices on spot forty\nsight hour coke, which have been around\n117 and $18 at the ovens.\nDespite the repeated banking caused by\nFailure of coke supplies, the blast fur-\nnaces managed to show a further gain j\nin production in June, with one day less\noperations. The output of coke and an-\n\u2018hraclte iron was 52.525 tons greater than I\nMay. The average daily rate of produc- I\nLion was 101.478 and 95.510 tons, and the\nLotals 3JM4.351 and 2,91,825 tons respec\n:lvely. All the month\u2019s gain was on the I\nfide of steel works\u2019 furnaces. Total first j\nlalf production of coke and anthracite i\nron was 18,151.244 tons, compared with I\n5.037.988 tons for the corresponding pe-\n\u2022iod in 1919 and 17,972.852 tons in 1918. The i\nake iron ore movement in June rose to j\n233.565 tons, a gf in of 1.242.S29 tons over\nlune, 1919, but a los sof 585.294 tons over I\nrune. 1918. which is the year the operator*\nirt attempting to duplicate. ,The ore\nwrought down to July 1 was 16,440,506 tons\nhis year, against 18,944,730 tons in 191k.\nConsiderable of a scramble for the Hm\nted offering of spot iron to stave off the\nhreatened shut downs continues among\narious consumers with resulting strength\n:o prices. The w'eek shows sales of east\nern Pennsylvania iron of 2.25 to 2.7 a\nsilicon at $49 and $50 furnace, and of Ala\nbama foundry in New England up to $67\nJeltvered.\nPotato Market\nBy AhnIiUI Prate\nChicago, July 8.\u2014Potatoes firm; Virginia\nGobblers. $12.25013 barrel; Southern Tri\numphs, $6.5007 per hundred; Kansas and\nRarly Ohio*. $6.7507\nV\nii nuuoc uirmuci iji wprn a numoer wmu\nhad achieved a high reputation for finan\ncial sagacity insisted that deflation wap\ntoo rapid and that the attempt to bring\nit about was made too soon. They went\nso far as to refer to Great Britain. There\nthe reserve of the Bank of England was\nas low ns 15 per cent. Here the re\nserve was maintained at 40 per cent.\nSome of the banks of the federal reserve\nsystem were carrying reserves in excess\nof 50 per cent, notably the Boston banks.\nThe average reserve was somewhere be\ntween 42 and 4.1 per cent.\nWHAT MR. MORGAN SAID\nReferences were frequent to the remark\nmade in 1907 by the late J. P. Morgan,\nwhen he was calling upon the banks for\nassistance in order that the panic in the\nfall of that year might he ended. Some\nbankers refused to comply, saying that\nif they did so they would be compelled\nto cut into their reserves. To these bank\ners Mr. Morgan said. \u201cWhat are reserve*\nfor except for use in emergency?\u201d That\nwas the opinion expressed by Frederick\nP. Tappan in 1900, and he always claimed\nthat reserves should be freely resorted\nto when business distress prevailed.\nNotwithstanding the low percentage of\nreserve carried by the Bank of England\nthe prevailing rates for money have beer\nsatisfactory. Great Britain through it?\nsufficient supply of currency and fund*\nhas been able to overcome some threat\nened business embarrassments.\nTherefore, the bankers who feared lest\ndeflation was too rapid and too drastic\nwere in favor of such action by the fed\neral reserve system as would make pos\nsible an increase of the currency, ever\nthough temporarily this might bring the\nreserve, down to 40 per cent or even lower.\nGradually the deflation group of banker.'\nhave changed their opinion. They nc\nlonger insist upon drastic cutting ot\nloans. They favor reasonable accommo\ndation for the business life of the coun\ntry. They believe that there should be\nsufficient currency in circulation to meet\nthe pressing demand c.f the business men\nfor accommodation.\nSo it has happened that with this\nchange of sentiment deflation has ended,\nthe chances for an increase in currency\n&re excellent, and the crisis which mary\nbusiness men apprehended in the late\nwinter and spring has passed. Now al\nJdok forward with contidence to business\nactivity and prosperity, not any longei\nfearing that drastic deflation will imperi\nbusiness activities and possibly product\nvery great business depression for a time\nSo that, it is the good news of these firs*\ndays of the new fiscal year that the dan\nger of business depression and of crisis\nhas passed.\nHEAVY SELLING AIN 1.)\nEXTREME WEAKNESS\nFEATURED CORN LIST\nOats Went to Good Losses, While\nProvisions Slumped Fifteen to\nSixty-two Cents\nBy Associated Press\nChicago, .July 8.\u2014Heavy selling: am\nextreme weakness developed in the\ncorn market today largely, owing tc\nchances that the government crop te\nport tomorrow' would prove bearish\nThe close was flurried. 3% to 5He nei\nlower, with September, 1.56 to 1.56H. and\nDecember 140 to 140%. Oats lost\nto 2He and provisions 15 to 62c.\nThrough tout the day sentimem\nagainst the bulls in corn was over\nwhelming and the only rallies whicl\ntook place were apparently due tc\nprofit taking by shorts. Liquidator\non the part of discouraged holders be\ngan to broaden out as soon as the mar\nket opened, and was still unabatei\nwhen the session came to an end\nMeanwhile continued liberal receipt:\ngave special emphasis to the view tha\nthere was a world of old corn bad\nin the country and (hat crop condition:\nwere giving promise of a new yielc\nmore than ample. Serious curtail.nen\nof feeding demand was also said to be\nin prospect. The sole important fac\ntor that tended to check weakness wai\nfear of prolonged cool weather.\nOats were relatively steady, owing\nto current opinion that farmers woulc\nnot accept less than seventy cents foi\ntheir new crop.\nAn upturn in the value of hogs liftec\nthe provision market. Packers v ere\nconspicuous on the buying side.\nChicago Futures\nBy Associated Press\nChicago. July 8.\u2014Future quotations\nwere as follows:\nCorn\u2014\nSept.\nDec.\nOats\u2014\u2022\nSept.\nDec.\nPork\u2014\nJuly _\nSept.\nJuly1*\nSept.\nRibs\u2014\nJuly\nSept.\nOpen.\n1.58\n1.43 H\nHigh.\n1.60\n1.43%\n1.\n1.40\nClose\n1.60\n1.40\n80\n76\n78%\n75%\n78%\n75%\n20.\u2019\n20.7\n28.25\n30.25\n18.(7\n1 0.30\n18.77\n10.65\n18.47\n19.20\n18.77\n1 9. j0\n17.37\n18.62 17.35\n16.75\n17.62\nNo.\n$2.i\n('ash Grafn\nBy Associated Praia\nChicago. July 8. (\u2019ash wheat,\nhard. f\\83; No. 1 northern spring,\norn. No. 2 mixed. $1.60ftl.61; No. 2 yt\nlow. 1.61 ft 1 62% Oats. No. 2 white. $1.03\n1.05%: No. 3 white. $1 03ft'1.05%. Rye. N\n2. $2.24%. Rarlev, $1.25ft 1.32. Timotl\nseed. $10ftl2. (\u2019lover seed, $25ft30. Poi\nnominal. T^ard, $18.77. Ribs. $16.25<q 17.25.\nRice Market\nBy Associated Presa\nNew Orleans. July 8.\u2014Rough riee no\nsales, receipts none. Clean rice steady,\nsales Honduras 868 pockets, 5% to 12%\nblue roses 2.695 pockets. 5%. Rran and\npolish unchanged, receipts 626.\nMARINE NEWS\nBy Asteeiatei1 Pr\u00ab*\u00ab\nMobile, July 8. Arrived: None.\nFailed: Glorietta. Havana: schooner \\V.\nH. Marston, *San Juan, Porto Rico.\nNew Orleans. July 8\u2014Cleared: Copan\n(Honduran). Omoa. via Port Cortez:\nGeorge W. Barnes. Tampico; Lake Bel\nnona. Porto Rico: Faramacoa, Port. Bar\nrios. via Belize: Yumuri, Vera crUz; bark\nOriole, Gulfport.\nPort Eads. La., July 8.\u2014Arrived\nAschenburg ('British'. Shields: Baldhill,\nMexico; Cosmos (British), Bristol, Eng\nland: Ceiba (Honduran). Ceiba; Gansf\njord (Norwegian), Bluefield; George vV.\nBarnes. Tampico; Lal:e Grainger, Porto\nRico; Lake I^arga. Panama: Omoa (Hon\nduran), Port Cortez; Parismina, Bocas\ndel Toro; Raeburn (British), Gulfport:\nKaranac (British), United Kingdom;\nTamesi, Tampico; Vologda (British),\nNorfolk:\nFailed: Comos, New York; Heredia. Bo\ncas del Toro, via Cristobal and Port Li\nmon; Kosciusko, Danzig, Pdland, via\nHamburg and Gothenburg, Sweden; San\nta Clara. Cardenas, Cuba.\nNEW ISSUE\nARMOUR Sl COMPANY\n7 Per Cent 10-Year Convertible\nGold Notes due July\n1930, at\n94.84 and Interest to Yield\n7% Per Cent\nSTEINER BROS.\nBankers\nBirmingham. Ala.\n'JULY COTTON GOES\nTO SHARP BREAK ON\nThe General Cotton Lisi\nShowed a Net Decline of\nForty-three to Forty\nseven Points All Round\nBy Associated Pres*\nNew York, July 8.\u2014A sharp break ii\nthe price of July contracts encourage,'\nmore aggressive selling of later deliv\ncries in the cotton market today, ow\ning to the continued favorable cro\nnews and reports of depressions in th\ntextile trade. October contracts sol\noff to 32.60c, making a net decline o\n62 points and the lowest price touche'\nsince last winter. That delivery close'\nat 32.84c, with the general list show\ning a net decline of 43 to 67 points o\nall months, except August and Sep\ntembe.r, which were 40 to 80 point\nhigher.\nThe market opened barely steady a\nan advance of 30 points on September\nbut 62 points lower on July and 10 t\n21- points lower on the active new crc\nmonths. Additional July notices esti\nmated at about 2.000 to 2,500 bales wer\nreported, and as these circulate'\nthrough the street, they brought on\nconsiderable liquidation. For a tim\nsellers of July found very tew buyer\naround the ring and before the declin\nwas checked July had sold at 38.50c\nmaking a break of 117 points from th\nclosing prices of yesterday and of 14\npoints from the hign level of yester\nday morning.\nThere was covering enough to caus\nrallies from this level in the late\ntrading, but the weakness of the near\nmonth stimulated selling on the tal\nof bearish mid-month condition figure\nand reports of increasing curtalimen\nin cotton yarn mills. All the activ\nnew crop months made new loi\nground for the movement, selling of\nto 31.17c for December, or about t\n67 points net lower. Moderate rallie\nfollowed on covering, hut were nr\nfully maintained, with December clos\ning at 31.20c. Reports that trustees ha\nbeen appointed for one of the bigges\nfirms in the silk trade seemed to in\ncrease pessimism over the goods sit\nuation, and there was considerable sell\ning here for southern account on th\ndecline.\nNpw York Futures\nBy Associated Press\nNew York, July 8.\u2014The cotton mar\nket closed steady.\nHigh. IiOW. Close\nJuly 39.40 HR.50 39.0\nOctober 33.12 32.60 32.8\nDecember 31.05 31.17 31.2'\nJanuary 30.90 30.50 30.0\nMarch 30.33 29.90 30.0\nNew Orle*Tt* Cotton\nBy Associated Press\nNew Orleans, July 8.\u2014A fresh displa\nof bearish sentiment today put th\nprice of cotton to lower levels, but to\nward the close the market acted over\nsold and realizing: by early seller\nchecked the downward movement an\ncaused small recoveries. The close wa\nat net losses for the session of 50 to 7\npoints. At the lowest levels the mor\nactive months were 64 to 79 point\ndown. July was not very active at an\nstage of the session. At its lowest I\ntraded at 36.65 while October fell t\n32.?5.\nThe opening: was lower in the far\nof the much better Liverpool mark*\nthan due and for a while the sellin\nwas aggressive so that in the earl\ntrading: prices were two dollars a bal\nand more, under the close of yesterday\nFavorable reports regarding: weathe\nconditions over the belt were mainl\nresponsible for the offerings, whlc\nwere further increased after the fore\ncast was posted, calling for dry weatli\nor over the entire cotton region.\nSupplementing the bearish weathe\nreturns were reports of fjuiet and easie\nmarkets for cotton goods in this coun\ntry while Liverpool cablegrams sai\nthat trade conditions in the Englis\nmarket continued unsatisfactory wit\nno prospects of immediate improve\nmerit.